To indicate the formula for the derivative of order "n" of the product of two functions, the formula of the binomial theorem is used symbolically.

The binomial theorem is closely related to the probability mass function of the <a href="negative%20binomial%20distribution">negative binomial distribution</a>. The probability of a (countable) collection of independent Bernoulli trials formula_77 with probability of success formula_78 all not happening is formula_79A useful upper bound for this quantity is formula_80. 

Formula (1) is valid more generally for any elements "x" and "y" of a <a href="semiring">semiring</a> satisfying "xy" = "yx". The <a href="theorem">theorem</a> is true even more generally: <a href="alternativity">alternativity</a> suffices in place of <a href="associativity">associativity</a>.

The binomial theorem can be stated by saying that the <a href="polynomial%20sequence">polynomial sequence</a> { 1, "x", "x", "x", ... } is of <a href="binomial%20type">binomial type</a>.





