and

Bessel himself originally proved that for non-negative integers "n", the equation "J"("x") = 0 has an infinite number of solutions in "x". When the functions "J"("x") are plotted on the same graph, though, none of the zeros seem to coincide for different values of "n" except for the zero at "x" = 0. This phenomenon is known as Bourget's hypothesis after the nineteenth-century French mathematician who studied Bessel functions. Specifically it states that for any integers "n" ≥ 0 and "m" ≥ 1, the functions "J"("x") and "J"("x") have no common zeros other than the one at "x" = 0. The hypothesis was proved by <a href="Carl%20Ludwig%20Siegel">Carl Ludwig Siegel</a> in 1929.





